## API Behavior Notes

This resource uses Microsoft Graph beta Application Proxy connector group endpoints:

- `POST /onPremisesPublishingProfiles/applicationProxy/connectorGroups`
- `GET /onPremisesPublishingProfiles/applicationProxy/connectorGroups/{connectorGroup-id}`
- `PATCH /onPremisesPublishingProfiles/applicationProxy/connectorGroups/{connectorGroup-id}`
- `DELETE /onPremisesPublishingProfiles/applicationProxy/connectorGroups/{connectorGroup-id}`

Microsoft Graph beta metadata lists `connectorGroupRegion` values `nam`, `eur`, `aus`, `asia`, `ind`, and `unknownFutureValue`. Direct API verification on 2026-07-05 returned the tenant default connector group with `region = "japan"`, which is not currently listed in beta metadata or represented by the generated SDK enum. The provider preserves that raw API value in state.

Direct API verification on 2026-07-05 also observed:

- `POST /connectorGroups` returned HTTP `200` with a connector group body, not the `201 Created` status shown in Microsoft Learn.
- Newly created connector groups returned `isDefault = false`.
- Importing the existing tenant default connector group returned `isDefault = true` and `region = "japan"`.
- Sending `connectorGroupType = "applicationProxy"` or `isDefault = true` in the create body did not fail, but Microsoft Graph ignored those read-only values and returned the system-managed values.
- `PATCH` for `name` or `region` returned HTTP `204` with no response body.

Microsoft Graph only allows `region` to be changed while no connectors or applications are assigned to the connector group.

The tenant default connector group is returned with `isDefault = true`. Because that connector group is system-managed, this provider does not attempt to delete it. If the default connector group is imported into this resource and later destroyed, Terraform removes it from state only and leaves the remote default connector group in place.

